<setup>
  
  <function name="v">3</function>
  <function name="s">3x</function>
    
  <point name="A" styleNumber="1">(0.25,-0.75)
    <constraints name="c1">
      <attractTo>$v</attractTo>
    </constraints>
  </point> 

  <point name="B" styleNumber="1">(1,-0.75)
    <constraints name="c2">
      <attractTo>$v</attractTo>
    </constraints>
  </point> 

  <point name="C" styleNumber="1">(1.75,-0.75)
    <constraints name="c3">
      <attractTo>$v</attractTo>
    </constraints>
  </point> 

  <function name="vDrag" through="$A $B $C" styleNumber="1" />  

    <point name="As" styleNumber="2">(0.25,-0.75)
    <constraints name="s1">
      <attractTo>$s</attractTo>
    </constraints>
  </point> 

  <point name="Bs" styleNumber="2">(1,-0.75)
    <constraints name="s2">
      <attractTo>$s</attractTo>
    </constraints>
  </point> 

  <point name="Cs" styleNumber="2">(1.75,-0.75)
    <constraints name="s3">
      <attractTo>$s</attractTo>
    </constraints>
  </point> 

  <function name="sDrag" through="$As $Bs $Cs" styleNumber="2" />  
  
</setup>
  


<p>
   Suppose that a person is taking a walk along a long straight path and walks at a constant rate of 3 miles per hour.
</p>

<p>
  <ol marker="a.">
    <li>
      <p>
        On the provided in the following figure, drag the three given points so they lie on the graph of the velocity function, <m>v(t) = 3</m>.
      </p>
      <graph grid="true" size="medium" xMin="-0.25" xMax="3" yMin="-2" yMax="8" fixAxes="true" showNavigation="false">  
        $vDrag
        <label anchor="(0.2,7.5)">mph</label> 
        <label anchor="(2.75,0.25)">hours</label> 
        $A
        $B
        $C
      </graph> 
      <answer><award><when>
         $c1.constraintUsed and $c2.constraintUsed and $c3.constraintUsed
      </when></award></answer>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Complete the following sentence to find how far the person traveled from <m>t = 0</m> to <m>t = 2</m>:
      </p>
      <p>
        Because the person traveled at a constant velocity of <m>2</m> miles per hour and we know that when velocity is constant, <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>distance = rate/time</choice>
          <choice>rate = distance * time</choice>
          <choice credit="1">distance = rate * time</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>, it follows that in this setting, their distance traveled, <m>D</m> satisfies
       <m>D = </m> <answer>3</answer> miles per hour <m>\cdot</m> <answer>2</answer> hours = <answer>6</answer> miles.
      </p>      
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
          How is the distance found in part (b) related to the area of a certain region under the graph of <m>y = v(t)</m> from part (a)?  Complete the following sentence to explain.
      </p>
      <p>
        Because <m>y = v(t)</m> is a horizontal line, the region formed by <m>y = v(t)</m>, <m>t = 0</m>, <m>t = 2</m>, and the <m>t</m>-axis is a <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>triangle</choice>
          <choice credit="1">rectangle</choice>
          <choice>circle</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer> with a base of length
       <answer>2</answer> (with units <q>hours</q>) and a height of length  <answer>3</answer> (with units <q>miles per hour</q>), so the area of this region is <answer>6</answer> (with units <q>miles</q>).
      </p>
    </li>  
    <li>
        <p>
          Find an algebraic formula, <m>s(t)</m>, for the position of the person at time <m>t</m>, assuming that <m>s(0) = 0</m>.  Note that you must state your answer as a function of time, <m>t</m>.  
        </p>
      <p>
        <m>s(t) = </m> <answer>3t</answer>
      </p>  
    </li>  
    <li>
       <p>
          On the axes provided in the following figure, drag the three given points so they lie on the graph of the position function, <m>y = s(t)</m>.
        </p>
        <graph grid="true" size="medium" xMin="-0.25" xMax="3" yMin="-2" yMax="8" fixAxes="true" showNavigation="false">  
        $sDrag
        <label anchor="(0.2,7.5)">miles</label> 
        <label anchor="(2.75,0.25)">hours</label> 
        $As
        $Bs
        $Cs
      </graph> 
      <answer><award><when>
         $s1.constraintUsed and $s2.constraintUsed and $s3.constraintUsed
      </when></award></answer>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p> 
        Finally, complete the following sentence to explain the behavior of <m>s</m> using using relevant information about the velocity function <m>v</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        We observe that the function <m>s(t)</m> is always <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>constant</choice>
          <choice credit="1">increasing</choice>
          <choice>decreasing</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer> on the interval <m>0 \le t \le 2</m> because <m>v(t)</m> satisfies <m>s'(t) = v(t)</m> and we know <m>v(t)</m> is always <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice>zero</choice>
          <choice>negative</choice>
          <choice credit="1">positive</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer> on the interval <m>0 \le t \le 2</m>.
      </p>  
    </li>
  </ol>  
</p>  
